### Set

A Set may be viewed as well-defined collection of objects called the elements or members of the set.
	- use capital letter to denote sets
	- lowercase letter to denote elements of sets 

### Subset
When every element of A is also elements of B then A is a subset of B

### Universal Set
All sets and elements belongs to a universal set which is denoted by U

### Empty Set
A set with no element is called a empty or null set

### Disjoint Set
Two sets A and B are said to be disjoint if they have no element in common

### Venn Diagram
A venn diagram is a pictorial representation of sets in which sets are represented by enclosed areas in the plane

### Union
The union of two sets A and B is the set of all elements which belong to A or to B

### Intersection 
The intersection of two sets A and B is the set of all elements which belong to A and B

### Complements
The complement of set A is the set of elements that belongs to U but not to A

### Differences
The relative complement of a set B with respect to a set A or, simply, the difference of A and B, is the elements which belong to A but which do not belong to B

### Symmetric Difference 
The symmetric difference of set A and B consists of those elements which belong to A or B but not both.
